poor that, if left unchecked, could lead to an increasingly divided society. Graham reveals how people who do not believe in their own futures are unlikely to invest in them, and how the consequences can range from job instability and poor education to greater mortality rates, failed marriages, and higher rates of incarceration. She describes how the optimism gap is reflected in the very words people use-the wealthy use words that reflect knowledge acquisition and healthy behaviors, while the words of the poor reflect desperation, short-term outlooks, and patchwork solutions. She also explains why the least optimistic people in America are poor whites, not poor blacks or Hispanics.Happiness for All? highlights the importance of well-being measures in identifying and monitoring trends in life satisfaction and optimism-and misery and despair-and demonstrates how hope and happiness can lead to improved economic outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican Dream. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 0aSocial mobilityzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Dream.  aHoratio Alger society.  aUnited States.  aaspiration.  abehavioral outcomes.  adespair.  adivided society.  ahappiness.  aincome distribution.  aincome mobility.  ainequality.  alife satisfaction.  amisery.  amobility.  aopioid addiction.  aoptimism.  apoor people.  apoor.  apoverty.  arich people.  arich.  astress.  awell-being measures.  awell-being.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400884971zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400884971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/co